definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To press forward ; to advance by pushing .
examples: The man crowded into the packed room.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To press together or collect in numbers.
examples: They crowded through the archway and into the park.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To press or drive together, especially into a small space; to cram .
examples: He tried to crowd too many cows into the cow-pen.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To fill by pressing or thronging together
( transitive , often used with "out of" or "off" ) To push , to press , to shove .
examples: They tried to crowd her off the sidewalk.

definitions.definition: ( nautical ) To approach another ship too closely when it has right of way .
( nautical , of a square-rigged ship , transitive ) To carry excessive sail in the hope of moving faster.
( transitive ) To press by solicitation ; to urge ; to dun; hence, to treat discourteously or unreasonably .
